---
description: Core rules for the legal-AI platform. Always applied.
alwaysApply: true
---

# Communication
- Reply to the developer in ENGLISH only. Code comments and commits in English.
- The APP defaults to Colombian Spanish (es-CO). en-US is the only other locale.

# i18n
- All user-facing copy lives in message catalogs (next-intl). Never hardcode strings in JSX.
- Locale resolution order: user preference (persisted) -> cookie -> es-CO default.
- Use Colombian conventions for date, time, and currency (COP) in es-CO.

# Theming
- next-themes with light / dark / system. A toggle is present in every app shell.
- Colors come from CSS variables / design tokens. No raw hex in components.

# Multi-tenancy (CRITICAL)
- Every tenant-owned table has a non-null tenant_id (the law firm that owns the row).
- Postgres Row-Level Security is enabled on every tenant-scoped table and enforces
  tenant_id = the requesting user's active tenant. RLS is the source of truth, not app code.
- Cross-tenant access exists ONLY for the platform operations role, via explicit policy.
- Write a test for each tenant-scoped table proving tenant A cannot read tenant B's rows.

# Auth (Clerk + Supabase third-party)
- Use Supabase native third-party auth with Clerk — NOT the deprecated JWT-template bridge.
- Client: createClient(url, anonKey, { accessToken: async () => (await auth()).getToken() }).
- RLS: auth.jwt()->>'sub' for user id (not auth.uid()); org_id for firm tenant scoping.
- Two scoping models: firm rows by org_id; founder/investor rows by sub ownership + deal grants.
- Firm templates/clauses reach founders only via server-side rendering, never direct SELECT.

# AI
- All model calls go through one internal abstraction (the AI gateway). Swapping providers
  is a config change, not a code change. Default provider: Anthropic.
- Cheap model by default (e.g. Haiku-class); escalate to a stronger model only for
  complex drafting, DD analysis, and executive summaries. Routing is configurable.
- Every customer-facing AI output passes the guardrail/validation layer before display,
  and every AI response renders with the standard disclaimer.
- Never reference Colombian laws or cases that are not in the provided corpus. If unsure,
  escalate; do not fabricate. Mark gaps as TODO(legal).

# Security & defensibility
- Master templates and clause libraries render SERVER-SIDE and never reach the client.
- Generated documents and data-room downloads are fingerprinted (user + session + tenant).
- Data-room previews carry a visible watermark (viewer name + access timestamp).
- Rate-limit document generation and data-room access per user/tenant/hour/day/month.
- Audit-log every meaningful action (who, what, when, from where, tenant). 3-year retention.

# Code quality
- Small commits. Keep BUILD_PLAN.md current. Typed end to end. No `any` without a reason.
- Server Components by default; Client Components only where interactivity requires it.
- Use proxy.ts (not middleware.ts) for Next.js request boundary routing.
- Compose Clerk + next-intl in the same proxy.ts (`export default clerkMiddleware(...)`).
- proxy.ts is a thin boundary: locale negotiation + optimistic session redirects only.
  Never put real authorization in proxy.ts — RLS and server components enforce access.
